In[914]:
# Step 1: Make sure everything is clean
gdp_long['country_code'] = gdp_long['country_code'].astype(str).str.strip().str.upper()
concordance['iso3_code'] = concordance['iso3_code'].astype(str).str.strip().str.upper()

# Step 2: Merge using gdp_long.country_code == concordance.iso3_code
gdp_merged = pd.merge(
    gdp_long,
    concordance,
    left_on="country_code",   # from gdp_long
    right_on="iso3_code",     # from concordance
    how="inner"
)

# Step 3: Check result

Explanation

The table below shows the average per capita protein supply across all countries at 5-year intervals based on the old methodolgy dataset:

In 1990, the average protein supply across all countries was about 69.78 grams/day.

By 2010, it had increased to about 79.84 grams/day.

This shows a steady growth of about 10 grams/day in global protein supply over 20 years.

Each 5-year interval shows an increase of about 2 to 3 grams.

Global dietary quality has improved over time, suggesting better nutrition and food availability.

C) IDENTIFICATION OF OUTLIERS AND REPLOTTING OF GRAPHS

In[925]:
# Firstly defining a simple function to remove outliers
def remove_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]

# Step 1: Remove outliers for GDP and Protein separately
# For OLD dataset
final_merged_old_clean = remove_outliers(final_merged_old, 'gdp')
final_merged_old_clean = remove_outliers(final_merged_old_clean, 'pcpdprotein')

# For NEW dataset
final_merged_new_clean = remove_outliers(final_merged_new, 'gdp')
final_merged_new_clean = remove_outliers(final_merged_new_clean, 'pcpdprotein')
In[926]:

New Dataset:

Conclusion:

  • Removing outliers improved the visibility of the underlying trend.
  • Both datasets confirm that wealthier countries have better protein availability, but the new dataset shows it more clearly.
